:::summary
Herodotus of Halicarnassus (c. 484–425 BC) is called the "Father of History" — the first person to systematically investigate and record the past as an object of inquiry rather than merely reciting myth and legend. His *Histories*, an account of the Greco-Persian Wars and the cultures surrounding them, is one of the most remarkable books of the ancient world: a work of immense curiosity, vivid storytelling, and genuine effort to understand why great events happen.
:::

